##Shanghai doctor at the Shelter Hospital: It is expected that people will be discharged soon

Function introduction, the interface news is China has the influence original financial and economic new media, only serves the independent thinking crowd

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Image: Tongji University Affiliated Oriental Hospital

Reporter: Liu Sunan Editor: Xu Fei



Most patients are relatively stable, most patients with only drug treatment or even can not take drugs.





Most patients are relatively stable, most patients with only drug treatment or even can not take drugs.



February 9,2:00 p.m. to the early hours of the next day, more than 100 patients arrived in Area B of the Wuhan Living Room Shelter Hospital. As they disembarked from the bus and entered the cabin, the workload of the medical staff ballooned, leaving one doctor to do the usual work of the residents and attendings alone.

The doctor on duty in Area B, Hua Jing, is from Shanghai. He is a physician in the East Hospital affiliated to Tongji University and a member of the China International Emergency Medical Team (Shanghai) . On Feb. 4, the 55-member medical team set out from Shanghai to reinforce Wuhan. On the evening of February 7, the rescue team officially entered the Living Room Shelter Hospital in Wuhan and began to treat patients.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Hua Jing's job is to complete the evaluation of the patient's condition, the writing of medical records, the issuing of medical orders, as well as all the patient's comfort and the treatment of special conditions. On the evening of the 9th, a class down, he admitted more than 30 patients, plus the previous shift, a total of more than 60 new patients, and he also had to deal with more than 200 patients in the area of emergency.

On Feb. 4, Wuhan began commandeering 11 venues to be converted into a "shelter hospital. " The Wuhan Living Room Shelter Hospital, where the Shanghai medical team is located, has beds separated into ABCD four zones, "compared with Zone A, zone B has more complete protective facilities. In the past, zone A had prepared its own long-sleeve shoe covers. In Wuhan, Zone B, it was ready. We still have enough protective equipment, " Hua said.

Patients with NCP are divided into four types: Mild, common, severe and critical. In principle, only the first two types of patients are admitted to the shelter hospital. At present, more than 1500 patients can be treated in ABC 3 district of Wuhan Living Room Shelter Hospital. Each district has 6-8 doctors and 16 nurses on duty.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Dr. Hua Jing, draw the map of the shelter hospital. Image: Tongji University Affiliated Oriental Hospital

On the 9th, Dr. Hua Jing entered the cabin for the second time. On February 8, he first entered the cabin and treated about 25 patients, this time about 35.

At the end of a night's work, he was impressed, "compared to Ward A, Ward B had a larger and faster influx of patients, and after entering Ward B, the patients moved around, and the head nurse used a high-pitched loudspeaker to persuade them to sit by the bed and wait to be examined, but the effect was not obvious. " He also admitted that because some of the new medical staff are still familiar with the environment, plus B area two doctors share a computer, the site work is still messy.

"How can we manage this kind of large living room ward more effectively? " Said Hua Jing, who would like to suggest that the Wuhan Epidemic Prevention Headquarters not only enhance medical care's familiarity with procedures and systems, but also mobilize the masses so that patients can learn self-management, the first thing to do with self-management is to stay put.

There are several reasons why patients aren't allowed to walk around.

One is that there are hundreds or thousands of people in the shelter, leaving very little room for patients to move around. If the patient moves around, doctors and nurses wearing a protective clothing vision only 90 degrees (usually 108 degrees) , inevitable collision with patients, may cause clothing damage, the risk is great.

In addition, wandering also delay the consultation, the doctor consultation when the patient is not in bed, or after the consultation found that the patient did not register in the nurse, it is easy to cause missed diagnosis, repeated diagnosis.

In addition, the entire area of the shelter is divided into contamination zones, buffer zones, clean zones, with different entrances for patients and medical care. Patients should avoid entering the clean area, otherwise it may lead to infection of health care workers in the clean area, leading to non-combat attrition.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
To prepare the patient for admission to the Shelter Hospital. Image: Tongji University Affiliated Oriental Hospital

Dr. Huajing noted that there were 12 patients in each cubicle in Ward B, often two or three young white-collar patients, most of whom had good personal qualities and management experience, "Make them dorm presidents, so that doctors and nurses can catch a sheep and manage them more easily. "

Working side by side with Dr. Hua Jing was Dr. Zhao Liming, a respiratory physician at the Oriental Hospital affiliated to Tongji University and a member of the China International Emergency Medical Team (Shanghai) . February 9 was also the second time he had been in the cabin, working from 2 p.m. until 9:30 p.m. "The suit makes you clumsy, " he said.

He said that this is the first time in China's contemporary history to establish a "shop-like" hospital. Each patient was given a warm military coat and the food was free and available on demand. As of February 10,1,213 patients had been admitted to the Shelter Hospital, and the number was growing rapidly.

Since entering the shelter, Zhao Liming has treated 42 patients, accounting for 30% mild cases and 70% ordinary cases. The so-called "ordinary" , refers to those who have lesions CT, clinical symptoms mild patients.

"WUHAN PEOPLE REALLY NOT EASY! " Zhao Liming emotion.

Among his patients was a 24-year-old man. His grandmother had died of new pneumonia, his mother was hospitalized in another hospital, and he and his father were admitted to the shelter hospital. "When I first met him, he was in low spirits. I went to comfort him and asked him about his mother. In the evening, when he heard that his mother was better, he began to feel better, " Zhao said.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The nurse does not have the infusion work, generally does not need to take care of the patient life, therefore the nursing operation is less, but maintains the order the work to be heavier in the initial stage. On February 10th, the cabin hospital admitted many patients over the age of 65 under the principle of collection, after which life care work will become heavier.

Zhao Liming found that most of the patients admitted to the general type of pneumonia, cross-infection, aggregation of the majority of disease, a longer course, generally more than two weeks. Therefore, he proposed to increase the deployment of medical staff and medical equipment, "only should be collected, it is possible to curb the spread of Wuhan Epidemic Momentum. ".

Huang Guoxin, a pharmacist in the Pharmacy Department of the Oriental Hospital affiliated to Tongji University and a member of the China International Emergency Medical Team (Shanghai) , entered the pharmacy in the Shelter Hospital after arriving in Wuhan.

"The people of Wuhan are too hard! I hope they get better soon! " From 8 pm on February 9 to 8 am on February 10, on a night shift, Huang Guoxin filled more than 1,500 bags of soup at the pharmacy, each containing 200 milliliters. "Chinese medicine is used to fight viruses. It's soup. It's made and distributed to the shelter on the same day. "

In addition to meeting the needs of patients in the shelter, pharmacists are also responsible for the daily use of medicines by medical staff, "We work 12-hour shifts, " he said. "But we also work on breaks. We are short-handed and any time the team members feel uncomfortable, we are One Call Away. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The team of pharmacists consists of 10 members from the provincial and municipal national emergency medical rescue teams, led by Shaanxi Pharmacists Lian Jiangping. Because the drugs are emergency dispatches from different places, finding them is difficult and irregular. Previously, Huang worked with a team of pharmacists to organize pharmacies, install refrigerator components, and draw drug distribution maps by hand.

As a result of wearing a mask for a long time, Huang Guoxin left a wide and long scar on his cheek and nose. He said that the rescue team was what it looked like during the war, "The ability to quickly assemble, quickly get into a combat situation and quickly gain the initiative and control of the battlefield is something that we have been training for a long time by the National Emergency Medical Rescue Team of Shanghai Oriental Hospital, so the skills of drug classification and filing can also be put to use quickly. "

With the opening of the shelter hospital, there's always good news. As of Feb. 10, most patients are stable, and most can be treated with or without medication, according to Dr. Hua Jing.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Photo: Tongji University Affiliated Oriental Hospital

"For those who do not take the medicine, it is taken early, or the medicine is almost over. There is also a local infection, and it is getting better. " He expects patients in the cabin to be discharged soon, but we need to meet the conditions of two recheck nucleic acid negative and imaging examination improved.

When Hua Jing was on duty, she met an older female patient. After seeing the medical records, all of the questions he asked were consistent with the patient's symptoms, and he even knew that the patient had a bird in his house. This let the patient oneself admire greatly to the Shanghai doctor at present, originally the daughter contacts good Hankou hospital bed, she does not plan to transfer again however. "I've met a wonderful doctor! " She said to her neighbor next door.

In the course of admitting patients, Huajing found that "some patients came in and wanted to go out. I asked him and he said he was afraid. " But he was relieved to see that some of the incoming patients were optimistic, "early, long-term patients tell their stories and experiences to new patients who are just starting to get sick. They hear their friends laugh and frown. Looking at the old patient who is talking loudly, the new patient will say to us, 'look at him, he has been ill for so long, and he is still alive and kicking. I can't be scared of anything. ' "

"The success of this campaign is not just about the essential staff, it's about the patients. If every patient is accountable to themselves, to the community, to the care, then this is a battle that can be won,"he said.
